<DOC><DOCNO> AP890809-0236 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-89 0118EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-09 0789</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0827</SECOND><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge heard the first in an expectedparade of guilty pleas when two brothers became the first tradersarraigned on charges stemming from a federal probe of fraudulenttrading at the world's largest futures exchanges.   Brian Sledz, 29, and James Sledz, 24, pleaded guilty Tuesday toone count each of violating the Commodities Exchange Act. The elderbrother also pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud, and theyounger to one count of mail fraud.   The brothers are among 46 traders indicted Aug. 2 in the FBIprobe of the Merc and the Chicago Board of Trade. Published reportshave said as many as 30 defendants are expected to plead guilty andcooperate with authorities.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Frederick Wang resigned as president of WangLaboratories Inc., the company founded by his Chinese immigrantfather, and the stock of the troubled computer maker jumped 20percent.   Analysts said Wang's resignation on Tuesday signaled thecompany's intention to get serious about its problems, whichinclude a recently announced $375 million quarterly loss.   The stock rose to $6.87{ a share from $5.75 a share on theAmerican Stock Exchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Yields on three-year Treasury notes fell tothe lowest level in 18 months as the government began a series ofhuge debt auctions intended to raise $44.5 billion this week.   The Treasury sold $10 billion in three-year notes at an averageyield of 7.93 percent Tuesday, down from 9.12 percent at the lastauction on May 9 and the lowest rate since averaging 7.42 percenton Feb. 2, 1988.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans took out $2.99 billion more inconsumer debt than they retired in June, the government reported,as the pace of borrowing slowed in part because of declining autosales.   The Federal Reserve Board said Tuesday that consumer credit inJune rose at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.1 percent, downfrom May's revised 7.3 percent rate. The May increase was revisedfrom $3.6 billion to $4.2 billion.   Consumer credit increased 8.5 percent over all of 1988.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ampco-Pittsburgh Corp., a low-profile metalmanufacturer, announced Tuesday it has acquired a 6.6 percentinterest in Midway Airlines Inc. and may attempt to take control ofthe mid-sized airline.   But Midway ``has no interest in being acquired'' and has not haddiscussions with Ampco-Pittsburgh, David R. Hinson, the airline'schairman and chief executive, said Tuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines pilots are supporting acontinuation of their 5-month-old strike, union officials said.   Air Line Pilots Association members meeting in Newark, N.J.,voted 203-15 Tuesday in favor of sustaining the strike, unionofficials said. Late Monday, Eastern pilots in Atlanta voted493-121 not to return to work.</TEXT><DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A year in corporate limbo ended for NordenSystems Inc. with the announcement that the subsidiary of UnitedTechnologies Corp. is no longer for sale.   The Norwalk-based manufacturer of radar systems and otherelectronic military equipment was put up for sale in April 1988,but UTC said Tuesday it decided to keep it after receiving offersit said were inadequate.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hoylake Investments Ltd. released details of itscashless offer for BAT Industries PLC, but BAT again advisedshareholders not to accept the offer valued at about $21.6 billion.   Hoylake said it values its stock-and-debt offer for BAT at theequivalent of $14.14 a share, but the stock closed at theequivalent of $13.65 a share Tuesday on London's Stock Exchange, up5 cents.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In a development that could helpSpanish-language television compete for advertising revenue,Nielsen Media Research said it has been selected to develop anational Hispanic television rating service.   The rating service will attempt to define the audience forSpanish-language programming among people who identify themselvesas Hispanic, information one executive called critical to thegrowth of the medium.   Nielsen, the leader in English-language TV ratings for nearly 40years, said Tuesday it had signed a multimillion-dollar contract todevelop the Hispanic ratings service with the two largestSpanish-language television operators, Univision Holdings Inc. andTelemundo Group Inc.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices climbed again Tuesday to another post-crash high asthe Dow Jones industrial average finished just under the 2,700 markin active trading.   The widely watched Dow average of 30 industrials rose 4.18points to 2,699.17, just 23.25 points short of the record highclosing of 2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.   Bond prices finished mixed.   The dollar fell against most major currencies.   Cotton futures prices surged; grain futures fell; crude oil andprecious metals futures rose; and livestock futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>